Customer Identity Contract

Defines the canonical enterprise Customer entity in a federated but semantically harmonized architecture.

This contract establishes identity keys, attribute authority, structural quality tiers, and enrichment boundaries required for certification and AI eligibility.

1. Canonical Entity Scope

A Customer represents a unique legal or natural person with whom the enterprise has or has had a relationship.

This contract governs:

Individual customers

Joint customers (where applicable)

Business customers (if included in scope)

Out of scope: marketing prospects without confirmed identity.

2. Identity Key Strategy
Primary Identity Key

Enterprise Customer ID (ECID)

Persistent

Non-recycled

Immutable once assigned

Matching Inputs

Used only for identity resolution (not authority):

First name

Last name

Date of birth

Tax ID / National ID (where legally permitted)

Email (secondary confidence)

Phone (secondary confidence)

Matching confidence levels must be documented:

Deterministic

High-confidence probabilistic

Low-confidence (manual review required)

3. Attribute Authority Model

Authority is defined at the attribute level.

Each attribute must define:

Designated System of Record (dSoR)

Effective System of Record (eSoR) if enrichment occurs

Update responsibility

Example:

Attribute	dSoR	eSoR	Notes
Legal First Name	Core Banking	Core Banking	Immutable after verification
Middle Name	CRM	CRM	Optional field
Date of Birth	Core Banking	Core Banking	Requires documentary validation
Email	CRM	CRM	Customer-updateable
Risk Rating	Risk Engine	Risk Engine	Derived attribute

No attribute may have multiple designated authorities.

4. Structural Data Quality Tiers

Quality tiers are structural, not compliance-based.

Tier 1 – Structurally Complete

Required identity keys present

No conflicting attribute authority

No duplicate ECID

Required core attributes populated

Eligible for AI training and high-trust automation.

Tier 2 – Structurally Inconsistent

Missing non-critical attributes

Conflicting attribute versions across systems

Partial enrichment mismatch

Eligible for limited AI usage with confidence tagging.

Tier 3 – Structurally Unresolved

Duplicate identity candidates

Conflicting primary identifiers

Missing required core attributes

Not AI eligible.
Requires remediation workflow.

5. Enrichment Boundaries

Federated systems may enrich customer data, but:

Enrichment does not override designated authority.

Derived attributes must declare lineage.

Downstream projections must not redefine canonical identity.

The contract governs the canonical layer, not local projections.

6. Certification & AI Eligibility

Customer records may be certified only when:

Tier 1 or approved Tier 2

Attribute authority documented

Identity key validated

Remediation backlog logged (if applicable)

AI systems must reference certified customer views.

